    "body": "### Problem\r\n\r\nCurrently `:Man` forces using separate window unless the current buffer has alerady `man` filetype. It can be simply achieved by adding simple modifier to `man.open_page`, for example as a fake modifier:\r\n\r\n```diff\r\ndiff --git a/runtime/lua/man.lua b/runtime/lua/man.lua\r\nindex ac15aff60..0657e4e9e 100644\r\n--- a/runtime/lua/man.lua\r\n+++ b/runtime/lua/man.lua\r\n@@ -716,7 +716,7 @@ function M.open_page(count, smods, args)\r\n   local target = ('%s(%s)'):format(name, sect)\r\n\r\n   local ok, ret = pcall(function()\r\n-    if smods.tab == -1 and find_man() then\r\n+    if smods.curwin or (smods.tab == -1 and find_man()) then\r\n       vim.cmd.tag({ target, mods = { silent = true, keepalt = true } })\r\n     else\r\n       smods.silent = true\r\n```\r\n\r\nIn practice I'd like to open man page by nvim from the shell without using `MANPAGER` environment variable. \r\n\r\nBy default I run `nvim` inside `systemd-run` container (I hope \"container\" it's the correct term) and have terminal related issues (probably because `man` is run outside the container, but `nvim` inside it). \r\n\r\nIn practice, the number of lines are not correctly refreshed after zooming in and out in tmux window.\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\n- allow opening man pages in the current window at least from `man.open_page`\r\n- optionally extend `Man` command to allow use it too",
    "closed_at": "2024-03-16T01:00:26Z",
